      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In gritty, real-life scripts, the \"model minority\" stereotype is often depicted as a character who is:\n\n- A high-achieving, Type-A Asian-American who is always impeccably dressed and mannered, often to the point of being seen as \"too perfect\" or \"trying too hard\".\n- A character who is obsessed with their career and will do whatever it takes to succeed, often at the expense of their personal relationships or well-being.\n- A character who is depicted as being extremely polite and deferential to authority figures, often to the point of being seen as \"too submissive\" or \"too eager to please\".\n\nThese characters are often written as being overly reliant on their intelligence and work ethic to get by, and are frequently portrayed as being isolated from their own communities and struggling to connect with their cultural heritage.\n\nThe \"angry black woman\" trope is often depicted as a character who is:\n\n- A loud, outspoken, and aggressive woman who is quick to anger and slow to calm down, often to the point of being seen as \"too emotional\" or \"too hysterical\".\n- A character who is depicted as being a single mother or a caregiver, often to the point of being seen as \"too burdened\" or",
